You can call this method from synchronous code using a completion handler, as shown on this page, or you can call it as an asynchronous method that has the following declaration:

code: func evictItem(identifier itemIdentifier: NSFileProviderItemIdentifier) async throws

inlineContent.text: For information about concurrency and asynchronous code in Swift, see
Calling this method turns a materialized item into a dataless item to free up disk space. For more information on materialized and dataless items, see
If the item is a document without local changes, this method deletes the local copy of the item’s content. If the item has local changes, it fails with an
error.

When called on a directory, the system recursively evicts the directory’s content. It deletes the content of any materialized files, and recursively evicts any subdirectories. After it has successfully evicted all the content, it deletes its list of the directory’s content, making the directory dataless. The next time the system accesses the directory, it requests a list of the contents using the
protocol.
If the system encounters a nonevictable child, eviction stops immediately, and the system calls the completion handler with a
error. The error includes information about the nonevictable child in its
property. The system may have evicted other materialized items, based on the traversal order.
The system calls the completion handler after it successfully evicts all items, or immediately when an error occurs. Eviction might fail with the following errors:
if the item had nonuploaded changes.
if the user has marked the item as nonevictable.
if the item has open file descriptors on it.
if the item has too many hardlinks.
Other
error codes if the system can’t access or manipulate the corresponding file.
